Both AJAX and `location.replace()` can be used to replace the contents of a page with the contents of a different URL without adding a new page to the navigation stack. However, they work in different ways and have different use cases.

### AJAX

AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) is a technique used to request data from a server without reloading the entire page. When you use AJAX to load new content, the URL in the address bar remains the same, but the content of the page is updated dynamically.

Here's an example of how to use AJAX to load new content:
```javascript
// Using jQuery
$.ajax({
  type: 'GET',
  url: 'https://example.com/new-content',
  success: function(data) {
    $('#content-container').html(data);
  }
});

// Using vanilla JavaScript
fetch('https://example.com/new-content')
  .then(response => response.text())
  .then(data => {
    document.getElementById('content-container').innerHTML = data;
  });
```
